messages.content:
Below is a simple HTML file that implements an IRC client connecting to `irc.h4ks.com` via WebSocket on port `8097`, joins the `#lobby` channel, and sends a message to the channel. The username format is `doesnmXXXX`, where `XXXX` is a random 4-digit number. The client also sends the message "hi doesnm, I am you" to the `#lobby` channel upon connection.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>IRC Client</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        #messages {
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            height: 300px;
            overflow-y: scroll;
            padding: 10px;
            background-color: white;
        }
        #input {
            display: flex;
        }
        #message {
            flex: 1;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px;
            margin-left: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Simple IRC Client</h1>
    <div id="messages"></div>
    <div id="input">
        <input type="text" id="message" placeholder="Type a message..." />
        <button id="sendBtn">Send</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        const ws = new WebSocket('ws://irc.h4ks.com:8097');
        const messagesDiv = document.getElementById('messages');
        const input = document.getElementById('message');
        const sendBtn = document.getElementById('sendBtn');

        // Generate a random username like 'doesnmXXXX'
        function generateUsername() {
            const randomNum = Math.floor(Math.random() * 10000).toString().padStart(4, '0');
            return `doesnm${randomNum}`;
        }

        const username = generateUsername();
        console.log(`Connecting as ${username}`);

        ws.onopen = () => {
            ws.send(`NICK ${username}`);
            ws.send(`USER ${username} 0 * :${username}`);
            ws.send('JOIN #lobby');
            ws.send(`PRIVMSG #lobby :hi ${username}, I am you`);
        };

        ws.onmessage = (event) => {
            const message = event.data;
            console.log(`Received: ${message}`);
            const messageElement = document.createElement('div');
            messageElement.textContent = message;
            messagesDiv.appendChild(messageElement);
            messagesDiv.scrollTop = messagesDiv.scrollHeight; // Auto scroll to bottom
        };

        sendBtn.onclick = () => {
            const messageText = input.value;
            if (messageText) {
                ws.send(`PRIVMSG #lobby :${messageText}`);
                input.value = ''; // Clear input field
            }
        };

        // Optional: Send message with Enter key
        input.addEventListener('keypress', (event) => {
            if (event.key === 'Enter') {
                sendBtn.click();
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Copy the code provided above into a text editor.
2. Save the file with an `.html` extension, for example, `irc_client.html`.
3. Open the saved HTML file in a web browser to start the IRC client.

### Notes:
- This is a basic implementation and may not handle all the nuances of an actual IRC protocol.
- Error handling is minimal, and additional features may be required for full functionality.
- Ensure your browser supports WebSockets and that the server is reachable.

